Ah, another delve into the glorious annals of human attempts to control the uncontrollable. You want to understand a piece of colonial legislation concerning a plant that has, for centuries, simultaneously sustained and slowly murdered its devotees? Fine. Just try to keep up.

## Legislation enacted to improve the quality of tobacco exported from Virginia

This, you see, was an act of desperation cloaked in bureaucratic ambition. It was the [Virginia General Assembly](/Virginia_General_Assembly)'s rather belated attempt to wrestle some decorum, and frankly, some actual value, back into its most lucrative, yet increasingly problematic, export.

**[Long title](/Long_title)**

*   An Act for amending the Staple of Tobacco; and for preventing Frauds in his Majesty’s Customs

A rather verbose way of saying, "We need to fix our primary cash crop and stop people from cheating the Crown." The "amending the Staple of Tobacco" bit refers to improving the fundamental quality and consistency of the product that formed the bedrock of the [Colony of Virginia](/Colony_of_Virginia)'s economy. As for "preventing Frauds in his Majesty’s Customs," that’s the polite way of acknowledging that poor quality tobacco often led to under-declaration of value and general smuggling, costing the British Treasury a pretty penny in lost duties. It seems some things never change; where there's profit, there's always a loophole or a deliberately substandard product.

**Citation** 3 & 4 Geo. 3. c. 3
**Enacted by** [Virginia General Assembly](/Virginia_General_Assembly)

**Part of a series on [Tobacco](/Tobacco)**

This act, of course, didn't exist in a vacuum. It was merely a single, albeit significant, chapter in the rather extensive and often sordid [history of tobacco](/History_of_tobacco). The plant itself, a member of the [Nicotiana](/Nicotiana) genus, specifically [Nicotiana tabacum](/Nicotiana_tabacum), has a complex story, from its indigenous uses to its global economic impact.

### History

The narrative of this particular legislation is intertwined with the broader [history of tobacco](/History_of_tobacco) in the colonies. The sheer volume of tobacco being cultivated had, for some time, outstripped the demand for *quality* tobacco, leading to a glut of inferior leaf flooding the market. This, predictably, depressed prices and tarnished Virginia's reputation as a premier tobacco producer.

### Chemistry

At its core, [tobacco](/Tobacco)'s allure lies in [nicotine](/Nicotine), a potent alkaloid. The quality issues addressed by the act weren't about the presence of [nicotine](/Nicotine), but rather the overall composition of the leaf, its preparation, and the undesirable elements that found their way into the final product, influencing the character of the [smoke](/Tobacco_smoke) produced.

### Biology

The cultivation of [Nicotiana tabacum](/Nicotiana_tabacum) in [Colonial Virginia](/Colony_of_Virginia) was a labor-intensive process, susceptible to various [tobacco diseases](/List_of_tobacco_diseases). The act aimed to ensure that only healthy, properly [cured tobacco](/Curing_of_tobacco) of specific [types](/Types_of_tobacco) made it to market, rather than diseased or poorly prepared leaves.

### Personal and social effects

The economic reliance on tobacco had profound [personal and social effects](/Health_effects_of_tobacco) on the colonists. Its [prevalence of consumption](/Prevalence_of_tobacco_consumption) shaped colonial life, from daily habits to the very structure of society. The act, by attempting to stabilize the market, had indirect consequences on the livelihoods of many, sparking both resentment and grudging acceptance. The [marketing](/Nicotine_marketing) of tobacco, even in this nascent stage, was intrinsically linked to its perceived quality, or lack thereof. Beyond economics, tobacco even found its way into [art](/Tobacco_and_art) and was often consumed alongside [other drugs](/Tobacco_and_other_drugs). The act was an early form of [tobacco control](/Tobacco_control), albeit driven by economic, not health, concerns. The [religious views on smoking](/Religious_views_on_smoking) and the broader [tobacco politics](/Tobacco_politics) of the era also played a role in shaping public opinion and legislative efforts. The entire system revolved around the act of [smoking](/Tobacco_smoking) and the role of the [tobacconist](/Tobacconist) in the supply chain.

### Production

From [cultivation](/Cultivation_of_tobacco) to [curing](/Curing_of_tobacco), the entire [tobacco industry](/Tobacco_industry) was under scrutiny. The act sought to standardize the quality of [tobacco products](/Tobacco_products) leaving Virginia's shores.

## The Tobacco Inspection Act of 1730

The [Tobacco Inspection Act of 1730](https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Tobacco_Inspection_Act_of_1730_1730) (often simply referred to as the Tobacco Inspection Act, though its full title holds more weight, like a particularly heavy hogshead of poor intentions) was a pivotal piece of legislation passed by the [Virginia General Assembly](/Virginia_General_Assembly). Its primary, and rather ambitious, objective was to finally improve the notoriously inconsistent quality of tobacco being exported from [Colonial Virginia](/Colony_of_Virginia). For years, the market had been flooded with a mixed bag of quality, from the decent to the utterly deplorable, which, as one might expect, did little for Virginia's reputation or the prices fetched by its planters.

This far-reaching law, championed by the decidedly pragmatic [Virginia Lieutenant Governor](/List_of_colonial_governors_of_Virginia) [Sir William Gooch](/Sir_William_Gooch,_1st_Baronet), brought about a significant shift in the colonial economy. Its impact was profound, primarily because it endowed newly established public warehouses with unprecedented authority. These institutions were not merely storage facilities; they were granted the power to outright destroy crops deemed substandard, a punitive measure that must have sent shivers down the spines of many a planter. More importantly, perhaps, these warehouses were authorized to issue bills of exchange. These slips of paper, essentially receipts for inspected tobacco, quickly gained acceptance as a form of reliable [currency](/Banknote) within the colony, effectively monetizing the crop and stabilizing its value in a way that the physical leaf often failed to do. This innovation alone fundamentally altered the flow of commerce and credit in Virginia, providing a more stable medium of exchange than the often-fluctuating value of tobacco itself.

The act centralized the inspection process, designating 40 specific locations across the colony where all tobacco intended for export or debt payment *had* to be brought. This was a monumental logistical undertaking, designed to impose a uniform standard where chaotic individual dealings had once reigned.

### History

The 1730 warehouse law was not, of course, born in a vacuum. It was the culmination of previous, less effective, legislative attempts to regulate the tobacco trade. A warehouse act from 1712 had made an initial foray into the regulation of public warehouses, recognizing the need for some oversight. This earlier act was subsequently amended in 1720, granting county courts the authority to close or relocate warehouses that were inconveniently situated relative to existing landings. While these earlier laws laid some groundwork, they ultimately proved insufficient to address the systemic issues of quality control and fraud that plagued the industry. The colonial economy, heavily reliant on tobacco, suffered through periods of "long depression" exacerbated by overproduction of inferior leaf and the resulting low prices. It became increasingly clear to influential planters and merchants, those whose fortunes were most directly tied to the health of the tobacco market, that more drastic and comprehensive measures were required. The prospect of consistently higher prices for a reliably good product, even with stricter controls, eventually swayed many of the powerful figures who might otherwise have resisted such intrusive regulation.

### Public warehouses

Melvin Herndon, in his aptly titled work, "Tobacco in Colonial Virginia ("The Sovereign Remedy")," provides a rather illuminating account of how these public warehouses actually functioned, or at least how they were *supposed* to function, in the wake of the 1730 act.

He notes that the year 1730 saw the passage of "the most comprehensive inspection bill ever introduced" by the [General Assembly](/Virginia_General_Assembly). This wasn't a sudden burst of legislative genius, but rather a reluctant acceptance of reality. The widespread knowledge that previous inspection laws had demonstrably failed to prevent the market from being swamped by unmarketable tobacco, coupled with a prolonged economic depression, finally shifted the stance of many influential planters and merchants. They recognized that the alternative—continued economic stagnation—was far worse than the inconvenience of regulation.

However, such sweeping change rarely goes unopposed. The act faced considerable resistance from certain English customs officials, who likely preferred the chaotic system that offered more opportunities for informal gains, and, quite ironically, from a segment of the large planters who had grown accustomed to the lax previous system, perhaps finding ways to profit from it. A prominent planter, shortly after the law’s enactment, voiced his displeasure in a letter to a London merchant, complaining that "This Tobo hath passed the Inspection of our new law, every hogshead was cased and viewed by which means the tobacco was very much tumbled and made something less sightly than it was before and it causes a great deal of extraordinary trouble." The sheer audacity of expecting a product to be *inspected* before sale, causing it to be "tumbled" and "less sightly," suggests a certain level of entitlement. Others grumbled that the new law led to the destruction of tobacco that, in their minds, "used to bring good money," conveniently forgetting *why* it no longer did. Another planter pointed out, with a touch of cynical wisdom, that the planter's own "name and evidence on the hogshead had much more effect on the price of the tobacco than the inspector's brand," highlighting the enduring power of reputation and personal connections over official stamps of quality.

This verbal disapproval, however, sometimes escalated. In a display of what one might charitably call "vigorous dissent," or more accurately, "criminal arson," some "villains" took direct action. During the first year of the act's implementation, two newly established inspection houses were set ablaze: one in [Lancaster County](/Belle_Isle_State_Park_(Virginia)) and another in [Northumberland County](/Northumberland_County,_Virginia). It seems that for some, the concept of a fair market was less appealing than the prospect of a good bonfire.

Despite the initial friction and outright violence, the essential features of the 1730 inspection law proved remarkably resilient. While it was frequently amended throughout the colonial period, these adjustments largely fine-tuned the existing framework rather than altering its core principles. The act made it unequivocally clear that no tobacco could be shipped, whether in the traditional large [hogsheads](/Curing_of_tobacco), smaller cases, or any other cask, without first undergoing a thorough inspection at one of the officially designated warehouses. This definitively prohibited the shipment of "bulk tobacco," which was often inferior, poorly packaged, and a prime vector for fraud and misrepresentation.

The inspection process itself was quite rigorous. Each warehouse was staffed by two inspectors, bonded officials who were legally obligated to uphold the quality standards. In the event of a disagreement between these two, a third inspector could be summoned to mediate and make a final decision, ensuring a measure of fairness and preventing deadlocks. These officials were not merely employees; they were under strict regulations, forbidden under "heavy penalties" from passing substandard tobacco, engaging in the tobacco trade themselves (a clear conflict of interest, one would hope), or accepting any form of "rewards" or bribes. Such stringent rules underscored the seriousness with which the colony, and indeed the Crown, viewed the integrity of its primary export.

Crucially, the act stipulated that *all* tobacco, whether destined for export or offered as payment for public or private debts, had to pass through the same inspection process. This solidified tobacco's role as a de facto currency in the agrarian economy of Virginia, ensuring that its monetary value was tied to its verified quality. Inspectors were required to open the hogshead, extract and meticulously examine two samples of the tobacco. Any "trash and unsound tobacco" found was to be immediately burned in a designated kiln within the warehouse, ideally in the presence and with the consent of the owner. If the owner, perhaps in a fit of stubborn optimism or denial, refused consent, the *entire hogshead* was to be destroyed. This was a stark deterrent against attempting to pass off inferior goods. Once the acceptable tobacco was sorted and repacked into the hogshead, it was stamped with the planter's distinguishing mark, the net weight of the tobacco, the tare (the weight of the empty hogshead itself), and the name of the inspection warehouse. This system provided a verifiable record, ensuring accountability and establishing a baseline of trust in Virginia's tobacco on the international market.

## Inspection locations

The act, with its characteristic colonial thoroughness, meticulously dictated the precise locations for these public warehouses. It was a logistical marvel, or perhaps a bureaucratic headache, depending on your perspective, scattering these inspection points across the vast and often difficult terrain of [Colonial Virginia](/Colony_of_Virginia). The sheer number and geographical spread of these 40 locations underscore the comprehensive nature of the law, aiming to bring every significant tobacco-producing region under its regulatory umbrella. These sites were strategically chosen, often at established landings or near major waterways, to facilitate the transport of hogsheads. The frequent mention of specific landowners, such as "upon [Col. Byrd](/William_Byrd_II)'s land" or "upon [Col. Randolph](/William_Randolph)'s [land](/Curles_Neck_Plantation)," also reveals the intertwined nature of colonial politics, land ownership, and economic infrastructure.

The act specified, with unwavering precision:

XLIII. And for settling the number of public warehouses, and appointing the places where the same shall be kept, pursuant to this act, Be it enacted and declared, That a public warehouse or warehouses shall be kept, and the same are hereby appointed to be kept at the following places, to wit:

*   For the counties of [Goochland](/Goochland_County,_Virginia), and [Henrico](/Henrico_County,_Virginia); at [Warwick](/Warwick,_Virginia_(Chesterfield_County)), upon Howlet's land; and [Shockoe's](/Shockoe_Bottom) upon [Col. Byrd](/William_Byrd_II)'s land, under one inspection.
*   At [Bermuda Hundred](/Bermuda_Hundred,_Virginia), upon William Eppes's lots; and [Turkey Island](/Turkey_Island_(James_River)), upon [Col. Randolph](/William_Randolph)'s [land](/Curles_Neck_Plantation), in Henrico county, another inspection.
*   In [Prince George](/Prince_George_County,_Virginia); at Appamatox Point, upon [Col. Bolling](/Robert_Bolling)'s land; on Col. Robert Mumford's land; and [Powel's Creek](/Powell%27s_Creek_(Prince_George_County,_Virginia)); upon [Mr. Bland's](/Richard_Bland_(burgess)) land, under one inspection.
*   At [Cabbin Point](/Cabin_Point,_Virginia), in [Surry](/Surry_County,_Virginia); and [Merchants](/Merchant%27s_Hope) [Brandon](/Lower_Brandon_Plantation), in Prince George County, under one inspection.
*   At [Gray's Creek](/Cobham,_Surry_County,_Virginia), in Surry, where the Agents houses were, and [Warricksqueak Bay](/Burwell_Bay), in Isle of Wight County, under one inspection.
*   At Swineherd's and Mr. John Soan's, in [Charles City County](/Charles_City_County,_Virginia), under one inspection.
*   At Waynwright's Landing, Isle of Wight; and Laurence's, in [Nansemond County](/Nansemond_County,_Virginia), under one inspection.
*   At the [widow Constance's](/History_of_Suffolk,_Virginia), at Sleepy-Hole Point, in Nansemond County, under one inspection.
*   At Norfolk Town, upon the fort land, in the County of Norfolk; and [Kemp's Landing](/Kempsville,_Virginia), in Princess Anne, under one inspection.
*   At Hampton, in Elizabeth City, upon Mr. Miles's lot, at Warwick Town, in the County of Warwick, upon Mr. Gough's lots; and at Charles river, Roe's storehouse, in the county of York, under one inspection.
*   At Hog-Neck, in James City County; and at [Taskanask](/Croaker,_Virginia), in New Kent, upon William Morris's land;
*   and [the Colledge](/History_of_The_College_of_William_%26_Mary), and [Capitol](/Capitol_(Williamsburg,_Virginia)) landings, upon [Mr. Holloway's](/John_Holloway_(Virginia_politician)) land, under one inspection.
*   At the [town of York](/Yorktown,_Virginia), where the agents house was; and at Gloucester town, upon capt. Hannar's land, under one inspection.
*   At Deacon's Neck, and [Poropotank](/Poropotank_River), in Gloucester County, where the agents house was, under one inspection.
*   At [Crutchfield's, upon Col. Page's land](/Hanover_Town,_Virginia); and Mr. David Merriwether's in Hanover County, under one inspection.
*   At [Todd's](/Aylett,_Virginia), in King and Queen; and [Aylett's](/Aylett,_Virginia) warehouse, in King William County, under one inspection.
*   At John Quarle's in King William; and at Mantapike, and Shepherd's in King and Queen County, under one inspection.
*   At Chamberlain's in New Kent; and Williams's ferry, in King William, under one inspection.
*   At [Urbanna](/Urbanna_Historic_District), where the agents house was; and major Kemp's, in Middlesex County, under one inspection.
*   At [Hobb's Hole](/Hobb%27s_Hole), upon the lands of James Griffin; and at [Bowler's ferry](/Bowler%27s_ferry), upon Adams's land, in Essex, under one inspection.
*   At [Naylor's Hole](/Naylors,_Virginia), upon William Fantleroy's land, where his prise houses now are; and the [mouth of Totaskey](/Totuskey_Creek), at Newman Brokenborough's landing, in Richmond County; both under one inspection.
*   At Layton's, in [Essex](/Essex_County,_Virginia); upon [Maddox Creek](/Mattox_Creek), at Martin's, in [Westmoreland](/Westmoreland_County,_Virginia); and [Bray's Church](/Leedstown,_Virginia), in King George County, under one inspection.
*   At [Falmouth](/Falmouth,_Virginia), upon Mr. Todd's lots in King George; and at [Fredericksburg](/Fredericksburg,_Virginia), upon Mr. Francis Willis's lots, in Spotsylvania County, under one inspection.
*   At William Glascock's landing, in Richmond; and at the Rolling House, upon [Deep Creek, in Lancaster County](/Belle_Isle_State_Park_(Virginia)), under one inspection.
*   At [Corotoman](/Corotoman), at Queen's Town, where the agents houses were; and on the land where the widow Davis lives, in Lancaster; and the Indian Creek, at the warehouses, in Northumberland County, under one inspection.
*   At [Wiccocomico](/Wicocomico), at Robert Jones's; and at [Coan](/Coan_River), at the warehouses in Northumberland, under one inspection.
